commitResults.messageBody:
When using unmark and delete, call to Storage.deleteFromFile function
fires, saving the information to data/tasks.txt

Storage.deleteFromFile does not delete the information from
data/tasks.txt properly, causing the program to crash in the next
instance of running

Let's,
* update the Storage.deleteFromFile method to properly delete information
from the data/tasks.txt
* fix the unmark/mark and delete commands to use the proper Storage and
Parser class methods

refactor: rename taskList field in TaskList.java to tasks
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, the field taskList in taskList.java is used to represent
an ArrayList of tasks

Rename the private field "taskList" to "tasks" throughout the codebase
to improve clarity and consistency, as well as to follow the
specified coding guidelines for the course

This refactoring does not change any functionality, only
the naming to better reflect the variable's purpose.

commitResults.messageTitle: test: add assert statements to ensure index is greater than 0
commitResults.messageBody:
Current methods in ParserStorage do not have any checks to ensure
whether the index of what they are getting is correct.

Any erroneous input from the user may cause the task to not be added
properly

Add assert statements to ensure that all the indexes are more than 0

This ensures that the data is properly parsed before being used.

commitResults.messageTitle: refactor: add assertCheck method to command class and subclasses
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, command subclasses are not checking whether their
Storage, UI, userInput and taskList dependencies are being injected
properly before executing the commands in the method.

This needs to change as the user has the option of using two different
UI classes depending on what type of UI the user is using. If the
dependency is not injected properly, it will cause the application to
not work properly.

Add a new `testAssert(String userInput, TaskList taskList)` method to
the base command class and called it in all command subclasses.

This change improves the robustness of our commands without altering
their functional behavior.
